# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: award-of-garden-merit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] The **RHS Recommended:** **Award of Garden Merit** is an award for plants by the British Royal Horticultural Society (RHS).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] It is based on assessment of the plants' performance under UK growing conditions.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] It includes the full range of cultivated plants, from annuals, biennials and perennials to shrubs and trees.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] It covers plants grown for specific purposes—such as vegetable crops, fruit, hedging, topiary, groundcover, summer bedding, houseplants, etc.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] It tests characteristics such as robustness, hardiness, longevity, flowering/fruiting abundance and quality, usefulness, and ease of cultivation.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] It pays particular attention to a plant's ability to survive and thrive in challenging conditions such as wind and frost.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] The RHS Recommended: AGM trophy symbol is widely used in gardening literature as a sign of exceptional quality, and is recognised as such by writers, horticulturalists, nurseries, and everybody in the UK who practises gardening.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] The Award of Garden Merit is a mark of quality awarded, since 1922, to garden plants (including trees, vegetables and decorative plants) by the United Kingdom, Royal Horticultural Society (RHS).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] Awards are made annually after plant trials intended to judge the plants' performance under UK growing conditions.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] Trials may last for one or more years, depending on the type of plant being analysed, and may be performed at Royal Horticulture Society Garden in Wisley and other gardens or after observation of plants in specialist collections.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] Trial reports are made available as booklets and on the website.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] Awards are reviewed annually in case plants have become unavailable horticulturally, or have been superseded by better cultivars.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] The award should not be confused with the Royal Horticulture Society's Award of Merit (AM), given to plants deemed "of great merit for exhibition" i.e. for show, not garden, plants.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] All-America Selections is an independent non-profit organization that tests new, never-before-sold varieties for the home gardener.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] Plants of Merit are plants selected for their outstanding quality and dependable performance for the lower Midwest United States.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] The RHS Recommended: Award of Garden Merit was reviewed in 1992, to increase its usefulness and prestige.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] Field trial results gained weight in the assessments and existing award-winning plants were reviewed in the light of more recent experience.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] The awards were to be reviewed at 10 year intervals from 1992, but this frequency has been increased to annually.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] The 2012/13 review, with advice from experts such as Royal Horticultural Society's plant committees, specialist societies, Plant Heritage National Collection holders and others, resulted in many changes.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] Nearly 1,900 plants lost their merit awards and more than 1,400 plants gained awards; the list included 7,073 plants after the review.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] Plants may be added to the Royal Horticultural Society "Sunset List" for rescission for several reasons, including unavailability to gardeners, better plants becoming available, affliction by pests or diseases, or insufficient uniformity.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-garden-merit] The "Award of Garden Merit" symbol represents a cup-shaped trophy with handles.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-merit] The **Award of Merit**, or **AM**, is a mark of quality awarded to plants by the British Royal Horticultural Society (RHS).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-merit] The award was instituted in 1888, and given on the recommendation of Plant Committees to plants deemed "of great merit for exhibition" i.e. for show, not garden, plants.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-merit] A higher exhibition award is the First Class Certificate (FCC) given to plants "of outstanding excellence for exhibition".
[src:award-of-garden-merit/award-of-merit] The Award of Merit should not be confused with the Award of Garden Merit (AGM), given to plants of "outstanding excellence for garden decoration or use", i.e. to garden, greenhouse or house plants.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] The competition is entered by the communities of towns, villages and cities.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Different categories exist for various sizes of settlements.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Groups are assessed for their achievements in three core pillars: Horticultural Excellence; Environmental Responsibility; and Community Participation.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Over 1,600 communities around the UK enter each year, participating in their local region's "in Bloom" campaign.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] From these regional competitions, roughly 80 communities are selected to enter the national Finals of RHS Britain in Bloom.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] It is a popular campaign, estimated to involve more than 200,000 volunteers in cleaning up and greening up their local area.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Since 2002, the awards have been based on the Royal Horticultural Society's medal standards of Gold, Silver Gilt, Silver and Bronze; the winner is the settlement judged to have most successfully met the rigorous judging criteria.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Judging at the regional stage takes place around June/ July; judging for the national stage takes place in August.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] The results for the UK Finals are announced in September/ October.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] The competition covers the UK, the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Floral displays play an important part in the contest, but the "Bloom" title is now, perhaps, misleading: in recent years the competition has increasingly assessed how all sectors of the local community are managing their local environment.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] In 2006, the RHS introduced the Neighbourhood Awards (now the It's Your Neighbourhood campaign), a grassroots sister campaign to Bloom, supporting smaller, volunteer-led community groups focused on improving their immediate environment.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] The history of the 'Bloom', as it is colloquially referred to, began in 1964 when Roy Hay MBE, a horticultural journalist, went on holiday to France during the *Fleurissement de France* and was enthralled by seeing the country "filled to overflowing with flowers, shrubs and trees all in full bloom".
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] His enquiries revealed that President de Gaulle had given orders to brighten up the country and the French Tourist Authority had set up the *Fleurissement de France* in 1959 (now called *Concours des villes et villages fleuris*).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Hay was so impressed that he approached the British Tourist Authority (BTA), and he and Len Lickorish, then Director General of the BTA, set up a committee to run a British version, "Britain in Bloom".
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] It was piloted by the British Tourist Authority in 1963 (Lewisham being part of that pilot), and went national in 1964.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Despite this impressive list, Roy Hay later reflected that the initial reaction of the horticultural trade and local authorities was lukewarm.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Nevertheless, regional committees were quickly formed, and in 1964 Bath became the first national winner.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] From 1964 to 1969 inclusive there was an overall national winner.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] From 1970, however, the competition was divided up into a range of categories, because of the difficulty of comparing settlements of different sizes fairly.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] The British Tourist Authority managed the competition until 1983 when the Government Department sponsoring the BTA felt that it should relinquish the responsibility.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] The Tidy Britain Group (the group responsible for the Keep Britain Tidy campaign, now known as EnCams) took over; it already had a long association with the competition.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] To mark the changeover, 1983 was celebrated as "Beautiful Britain in Bloom Year".
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Sir Lawrie Barratt of Barratt Developments expressed his support to the Tidy Britain Group for the competition and provided sponsorship until 1989.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] More categories and awards were added, in part reflecting a greater range of settlements, but also to recognise other elements of horticulture, including landscaping, and also to recognise the strenuous efforts to beautify the urban areas of the larger cities.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] McDonald's began sponsoring the competition from 1990, which led to focus on littering behaviour and the implementation of a Children's Painting Competition Calendar.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] In 2001, the event was organised jointly by EnCams and the Royal Horticultural Society, and from November 2001 the RHS took full control as the organising body of Britain in Bloom.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] In 2017, after winning Britain in Bloom Champion of Champions, Elswick admitted to having previously cheated in the competition three years earlier.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] The volunteers engaged a specialist company to design a display which came in ready assembled trays.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Paul Hayhurst, Chairman of Elswick Parish Council and Elswick in Bloom co-ordinator, said "This result is entirely down to the hard work of volunteers in Elswick who have transformed our village".
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] The Parish Council accounts for 2017-18 contradict this statement though as they show the local lengthsman was paid £3,500 to plant summer plants.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] In September 2025, Paul Hayhurst, who had remained as Elswick in Bloom co-ordinator, informed the public that Elswick would no longer be entering the competition.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Paul Hayhurst stated that the chairman of North West in Bloom has been "quite rude" when he came to judge the village.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Elswick were later withdrawn from the competition before the results were announced.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] The competition currently has twelve entry categories, most of which are determined by population size.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Within each category, similarly sized communities compete across a spectrum of horticultural endeavour, community participation and environmental responsibility, which includes dealing with issues of litter, graffiti and vandalism.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] RHS Britain in Bloom encompasses 18 Regions/ Nations (12 English regions, as well as Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland, Isle of Man, Jersey and Guernsey).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] From the winners and finalists of RHS Britain in Bloom, entries are picked to represent Britain in international competitions such as the *Entente Florale*.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] There are 18 Regions/ Nations "in Bloom", each of which coordinate regional campaigns in their area.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] RHS It's Your Neighbourhood is part of the wider RHS Britain in Bloom initiative, helping volunteer-led groups to improve their local area.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Any group can take part, as long as it is volunteer-led and involved in hands-on community gardening.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] It should also be working with the community for the benefit of the community.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Participating groups care for all sorts of spaces - from local parks and gardens, to odd grot-spots which have been transformed and shared residential spaces or alleyways.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] The campaign was launched by the RHS in 2006 to support grassroots community gardening and there are currently more than 1,300 registered groups.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] The initiative works around the same three pillars of assessment as RHS Britain in Bloom: Community Participation, Gardening Achievement and Environmental Responsibility; however, it is not a competitive campaign.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Participating groups receive an annual visit from an It's Your Neighbourhood assessor, who provides feedback and tips for how to develop projects, and each group receives a certificate of achievement from the RHS.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] It's Your Neighbourhood is free to enter and open to groups of all sizes.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Winning a category within Britain in Bloom at a national or even regional level has proved to be a source of considerable civic pride for the towns, cities and villages involved.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/britain-in-bloom] Many of the authorities of the winning locations do advertise their achievements on signs within, or more predominantly on the outskirts of their settlement.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The **RHS Chelsea Flower Show**, formally known as the **Great Spring Show**, is a garden show held for five days in May by the Royal Horticultural Society (RHS) in the grounds of the Royal Hospital Chelsea in Chelsea, London.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Held at Chelsea since 1912, the show is attended by members of the British royal family.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Highlights to the Chelsea Flower Show include the avant-garde show gardens designed by leading names with Floral Marquee at the centrepiece.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The Show also features smaller gardens such as the Artisan and Urban Gardens.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The first Royal Horticultural Society Great Spring Show was held in 1862, at the RHS garden in Kensington.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Before this date the RHS had held flower shows from 1833 in their garden in Chiswick, which themselves had been preceded by fetes.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The Kensington Garden was chosen as a site because the flower shows in Chiswick were experiencing falling visitor numbers due to problems such as poor transport links.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The Great Spring Show was held at Kensington for twenty-six years but in 1888 the RHS decided to move the show to the heart of London.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The site chosen was the Temple Gardens, situated between the Embankment and Fleet Street, which had a recorded history dating back to 1307 and which were said to date from the time of the Knights Templar.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The roses for which these Temple Gardens were famous were alluded to in Shakespeare's *Henry VI Part 1*.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Using three marquees requisitioned from the old Kensington shows, the 1888 show was a success with exhibits from both amateurs and commercial firms.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] By 1897 five marquees were being used with many of the best known plant and seed merchants being attracted to the event including Suttons and Sons.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] In 1912, the Temple Show was cancelled to make way for the Royal International Horticultural Exhibition.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Sir Harry Veitch, the great nurseryman, secured the grounds of the Royal Hospital, Chelsea for this one-off event.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] It proved such a good site for an exhibition that the Great Spring Show was moved there in 1913, where it has taken place almost every year since.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] There have been two breaks for world wars.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The RHS first became involved with the Chelsea Hospital in 1905.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Three years before, it had leased the grounds of Holland House in Kensington to hold what was first advertised as a Coronation Rose Show, but which turned into a more general show (with not many roses) by the time it actually opened in June.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Two further two-day summer shows took place at Holland House in 1903 and 1904, but then, to the general satisfaction of exhibitors and press, a three-day Summer Show was staged in the hospital grounds, a more spacious site than Holland House had allowed, with room for five tents.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The Summer Shows reverted to Holland House for the years thereafter, except in 1911, when both it and Chelsea proved unavailable, and the Show was held at the Olympia exhibition hall.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The Royal International Horticultural Exhibition of 1912 used the grounds of Chelsea Hospital as the site for the show, and for 1913, the Great Spring Show was moved there.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The first Chelsea Flower Show opened on 20 May.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The Summer Show reverted to Holland House.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Despite the First World War, the show was held 1914–1916, but was cancelled in 1917 and 1918.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] By the 1920s, the Chelsea Flower Show had returned to its previous form; the famous Chelsea tea parties were established and Royal visits resumed.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] In 1926 the show was held a week late due to the General Strike.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] In 1937, King George VI and Queen Elizabeth celebrated their Coronation Year, and an Empire Exhibition was staged to mark the occasion.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] It featured wattles from Australia, pines from Canada, gladioli from East Africa and even a prickly pear from Palestine.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The show was cancelled during the Second World War, as the land was required by the War Office for an anti-aircraft site.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Some doubt arose as to whether the show would resume in 1947.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The majority of exhibitors wanted a postponement, as stocks of plants were low, staff much depleted and fuel for greenhouses was obtainable only with special permits, but Lord Aberconway (then RHS President) and the RHS Council felt strongly that the show should resume as soon as possible.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The show eventually successfully went ahead in 1947, but with a reduced amount of stands.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] In 1951 a show garden based on the Himalayan flora meant that 23 truck loads of plants were borrowed from RHS Wisley.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The Queen attended in 1953, the year of her coronation, and she was also a regular visitor prior to this date with her father, George VI.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The show went on to increase in popularity throughout the second half of the 20th century and crowding became a major problem.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Crowding within the tents had been a recurring issue during the interwar years, but was always handled by increasing the number of tents; photographs show heavy crowds in the open, especially in the vicinity of the rock gardens.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] As the 1970s progressed, attendance at the show climbed by 6,000 visitors in a single year (1978).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] In 1979, crowding became so severe in the mornings that the turnstiles were temporarily closed.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The new arrangements for the show were successful in 1980, and a majority of the Council voted for the imposition of a ceiling on the number of tickets sold.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] However, visitor numbers continued to increase, and in 1987 the turnstiles were closed again.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] In 1988 a cap had to be placed on the number of visitors attending the show due to problems that were occurring with overcrowding.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] A limit of 40,000 visitors per day was imposed – a reduction of 90,000 in total from the previous year – and members were charged for tickets for the first time.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] An immediate response was a fall in attendance; by April, ticket booking was so slow that national advertisements were taken out to encourage people to come to Chelsea, and the original announcement that tickets would not be available at the gates was rescinded.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] In response to issues with attendance numbers, the council began to look seriously at the idea of moving the show to a larger venue.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Battersea Park, Osterley Park, and Wisley were suggested; one proposal was that Chelsea should be limited to plant sales, and the sundries rerouted elsewhere; the firm Land Use Consultants was also hired to prepare a feasibility study.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] However, after considering these options, it was concluded that the show should stay at Chelsea.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Despite this, the show's programme was expanded into other venues, with the Hampton Court Palace Flower Show taken over in 1993; the increased options for both members and for exhibitors meant that the intense criticisms and conflict of the 1980s over the future of the show did not return.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The Chelsea Flower Show is attended by 157,000 visitors each year (a number limited by the capacity of the 11-acre (4.5 ha) ground), and all tickets must be purchased in advance.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] From 2005 the show was increased from four days to five, with the first two days only open to RHS members.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The show is extensively covered on television by the BBC.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] An official DVD of the show is produced on behalf of the RHS by ONE TWO FOUR.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Several members of the British royal family attend a preview of the show, as part of the royal patronage of the RHS.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The area of land devoted to show gardens increased steadily between 1970 and 2000 and the show has become an important venue for watching trends.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] New plants are often launched at the show and the popularity of older varieties revived under the focus of the horticultural world.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Highlights from the 2011 RHS Chelsea Flower Show included The Irish Sky Garden by Diarmuid Gavin, based on the idea of a restaurant in the sky.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Other notable gardens included the HESCO Garden by Leeds City Council, who reconstructed an impressive and idyllic working water wheel in the grounds of the Royal Hospital.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The 2011 show also saw the introduction of the new Artisan garden category, which was created for designers who use natural materials.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] In 2023, King Charles III and Queen Camilla attended the show and viewed a special display to pay tribute to the life of Queen Elizabeth II and to mark their coronation.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Catherine, Princess of Wales, hosted the first children's picnic at a newly created garden at the show with pupils from ten schools from the RHS's school gardening campaign invited.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Since 2022 the show has been sponsored by The Newt in Somerset.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] In 2025, daytime coverage was broadcast on BBC One and BBC Two in the evening.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] The shows were broadcast by a range of gardening experts and broadcasters including Monty Don, Carol Klein, Sue Kent, Sophie Raworth, Angellica Bell, Nicki Chapman, Jo Whiley, Toby Buckland and Frances Tophill.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] There are four grades of award presented – gold, silver-gilt, silver and bronze – in each of the awards categories.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/chelsea-flower-show] Bronze grade exhibits do not actually receive a medal.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/château-de-courson] The **Château de Courson** was built in 1676 in Courson-Monteloup, on the south-west outskirts of Paris, France.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/château-de-courson] It is in the Essonne *département* of the Île-de-France *région*.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/château-de-courson] Originally the home of the Lamoignon family, the château has been in the family of de Nervaux-Loys since the 18th century.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/château-de-courson] Its historic park was laid out in formal style by a pupil of André Le Nôtre in the 18th century.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/château-de-courson] During the 19th century the gardens were twice remodelled, first around 1820 for the Duc de Padoue by the landscaper Berthault, then again around 1860 by the Bülhers, who laid out many French parks and gardens, including those of Rennes, Lyon and Bordeaux.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/château-de-courson] The documentary film *Bring On the Night* about rock musician Sting's first solo tour was filmed at the château in 1985.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/château-de-courson] It is now most famous as the venue for the **Journées des Plantes de Courson**.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/château-de-courson] These extremely popular plant fairs were held in the grounds of the château in October from 1983 and also, from 1987, a spring plant fair was held in mid-May, until 2015, when the whole event transferred to the Domaine de Chantilly.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/château-de-courson] The château and park are still open for tours and other events.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] A **cultivar** is a kind of cultivated plant that people have selected for desired traits and which retains those traits when propagated.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Methods used to propagate cultivars include division, root and stem cuttings, offsets, grafting, tissue culture, or carefully controlled seed production.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Most cultivars arise from deliberate human manipulation, but some originate from wild plants that have distinctive characteristics.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Cultivar names are chosen according to rules of the International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants (ICNCP), and not all cultivated plants qualify as cultivars.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Horticulturists generally believe the word *cultivar* was coined as a term meaning "**cultivated variety**".
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Popular ornamental plants like roses, camellias, daffodils, rhododendrons, and azaleas are commonly cultivars produced by breeding and selection or as sports, for floral colour or size, plant form, or other desirable characteristics.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Similarly, the world's agricultural food crops are almost exclusively cultivars that have been selected for characters such as improved yield, flavour, and resistance to disease.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Since the advent of genetic engineering in the 1970s and the rise of its application in crop breeding in the 1980s, very few wild plants are used as commercial food sources.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Trees used in forestry are also special selections grown for their enhanced quality and yield of timber, for example American timber company Weyerhaeuser is the leading grower of genetically modified Douglas-fir trees, one of the most commonly harvested trees.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Cultivars form a major part of Liberty Hyde Bailey's broader group, the cultigen, which is defined as a plant whose origin or selection is primarily due to intentional human activity.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] A cultivar is not the same as a botanical variety, which is a taxonomic rank below subspecies, and there are differences in the rules for creating and using the names of botanical varieties and cultivars.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Since the creation of the Plant Patent Act of 1930 the naming of cultivars has been complicated by the use of statutory patents for plants and recognition of plant breeders' rights.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (UPOV – French: *Union internationale pour la protection des obtentions végétales*) offers legal protection of plant cultivars to persons or organisations that introduce new cultivars to commerce.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] UPOV requires that a cultivar be "distinct", "uniform", and "stable".
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] To be "distinct", it must have characters that easily distinguish it from any other named cultivar.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] To be "uniform" and "stable", the cultivar must retain these characters in repeated propagation.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The naming of cultivars is an important aspect of cultivated plant taxonomy, and the correct naming of a cultivar is prescribed by the Rules and Recommendations of the *International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants* (ICNCP, often called the *Cultivated Plant Code*).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] A cultivar is given a cultivar name, which consists of the scientific Latin botanical name followed by a cultivar epithet.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The cultivar epithet is usually in a vernacular language, and must be so for cultivars named after 1 January 1959.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The word *cultivar* originated from the need to distinguish between wild plants and those with characteristics that arose in cultivation, presently denominated *cultigens*.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] This distinction dates to the Greek philosopher Theophrastus (370–285 BC), the "Father of Botany", who was keenly aware of this difference.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants uses as its starting point for modern botanical nomenclature the Latin names in Linnaeus' (1707–1778) *Species Plantarum* (tenth edition) and *Genera Plantarum* (fifth edition).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] In *Species Plantarum*, Linnaeus enumerated all plants known to him, either directly or from his extensive reading.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] He recognised the rank of varietas (botanical "variety", a rank below that of species and subspecies) and he indicated these varieties with letters of the Greek alphabet, such as α, β, and δ, before the varietal name, rather than using the abbreviation "var." as is the present convention.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Most of the varieties that Linnaeus enumerated were of "garden" origin rather than being wild plants.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] In time the need to distinguish between wild plants and those with variations that had been cultivated increased.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] In the nineteenth century many "garden-derived" plants were given horticultural names, sometimes in Latin and sometimes in a vernacular language.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] From *circa* the 1900s, cultivated plants in Europe were recognised in the Scandinavian, Germanic, and Slavic literature as *stamm* or *sorte*, but these words could not be used internationally because, by international agreement, any new denominations had to be in Latin.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] In the twentieth century an improved international nomenclature was proposed for cultivated plants.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] In that essay, Bailey used only the rank of species for the cultigen, but it was obvious to him that many domesticated plants were more like botanical varieties than species, and that realisation appears to have motivated the suggestion of the new category of *cultivar*.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] It is generally assumed to be a blend of ***culti**vated* and ***var**iety* but Bailey never explicitly stated his choice of etymology, and it has been suggested that the word is actually a blend of ***culti**gen* and ***var**iety*.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The neologism *cultivar* was promoted as "euphonious" and "free from ambiguity".
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The first *Cultivated Plant Code* of 1953 subsequently commended its use, and by 1960 it had achieved common international acceptance.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The words *cultigen* and *cultivar* may be confused with each other.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] A *cultigen* is any plant that is deliberately selected for or altered in cultivation, as opposed to an *indigen*; the *Cultivated Plant Code* states that cultigens are "maintained as recognisable entities solely by continued propagation".
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Cultigens can have names at any of many taxonomic ranks, including those of grex, species, cultivar group, variety, form, and cultivar; and they may be plants that have been altered in cultivation, including by genetic modification, but have not been formally denominated.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] A cultigen or a component of a cultigen can be accepted as a cultivar if it is recognisable and has stable characters.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Therefore, all cultivars are cultigens, because they are cultivated, but not all cultigens are cultivars, because some cultigens have not been formally distinguished and named as cultivars.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The *Code* then defines a *cultivar* as a "taxonomic unit within the classification category of cultivar".
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] This is the sense of *cultivar* that is most generally understood and which is used as a general definition.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] A cultivar may be given a vernacular name or a number.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Which plants are chosen to be named as cultivars is simply a matter of convenience as the category was created to serve the practical needs of horticulture, agriculture, and forestry.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Members of a particular cultivar are not necessarily genetically identical.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The *Cultivated Plant Code* emphasizes that different cultivated plants may be accepted as different cultivars, even if they have the same genome, while cultivated plants with different genomes may be regarded as the same cultivar.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The production of cultivars generally entails considerable human involvement although in a few cases it may be as little as simply selecting variation from plants growing in the wild (whether by collecting growing tissue to propagate from or by gathering seed).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Cultivars generally occur as ornamentals and food crops: *Malus* 'Granny Smith' and *Malus* 'Red Delicious' are cultivars of apples propagated by cuttings or grafting, *Lactuca* 'Red Sails' and *Lactuca* 'Great Lakes' are lettuce cultivars propagated by seeds.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Named cultivars of *Hosta* and *Hemerocallis* plants are cultivars produced by micropropagation or division.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Cultivars that are produced asexually are genetically identical and known as clones; this includes plants propagated by division, layering, cuttings, grafts, and budding.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The propagating material may be taken from a particular part of the plant, such as a lateral branch, or from a particular phase of the life cycle, such as a juvenile leaf, or from aberrant growth as occurs with witch's broom.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Plants whose distinctive characters are derived from the presence of an intracellular organism may also form a cultivar provided the characters are reproduced reliably from generation to generation.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Plants of the same chimera (which have mutant tissues close to normal tissue) or graft-chimeras (which have vegetative tissue from different kinds of plants and which originate by grafting) may also constitute a cultivar.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Some cultivars "come true from seed", retaining their distinguishing characteristics when grown from seed.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Such plants are termed a "variety", "selection", or "strain" but these are ambiguous and confusing words that are best avoided.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] In general, asexually propagated cultivars grown from seeds produce highly variable seedling plants, and should not be labelled with, or sold under, the parent cultivar's name.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Seed-raised cultivars may be produced by uncontrolled pollination when characteristics that are distinct, uniform and stable are passed from parents to progeny.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Some are produced as "lines" that are produced by repeated self-fertilisation or inbreeding or "multilines" that are made up of several closely related lines.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Sometimes they are F1 hybrids which are the result of a deliberate repeatable single cross between two pure lines.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] A few F2 hybrid seed cultivars also exist, such as *Achillea* 'Summer Berries'.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Some cultivars are agamospermous plants, which retain their genetic composition and characteristics under reproduction.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Occasionally cultivars are raised from seed of a specially selected provenance – for example the seed may be taken from plants that are resistant to a particular disease.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Genetically modified plants with characteristics resulting from the deliberate implantation of genetic material from a different germplasm may form a cultivar.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] However, the International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants notes, "In practice such an assemblage is often marketed from one or more lines or multilines that have been genetically modified.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Cultivars may be selected because of a change in the ploidy level of a plant which may produce more desirable characteristics.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Every cultivar has a unique name within its denomination class (which is almost always the genus).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Names of cultivars are regulated by the *International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants*, and may be registered with an International Cultivar Registration Authority (ICRA).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] There are sometimes separate registration authorities for different plant types such as roses and camellias.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] In addition, cultivars may be associated with commercial marketing names referred to in the *Cultivated Plant Code* as "trade designations" (see below).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] A *cultivar name* consists of a botanical name (of a genus, species, infraspecific taxon, interspecific hybrid or intergeneric hybrid) followed by a cultivar epithet.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The cultivar epithet is enclosed by single quotes; it should not be italicised if the botanical name is italicised; and each of the words within the epithet is capitalised (with some permitted exceptions such as conjunctions).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] It is permissible to place a cultivar epithet after a common name provided the common name is botanically unambiguous.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Cultivar epithets published before 1 January 1959 were often given a Latin form and can be readily confused with the specific epithets in botanical names; after that date, newly coined cultivar epithets must be in a modern vernacular language to distinguish them from botanical epithets.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] For example, the full cultivar name of the King Edward potato is *Solanum tuberosum* 'King Edward'.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] 'King Edward' is the cultivar epithet, which, according to the Rules of the *Cultivated Plant Code*, is bounded by single quotation marks.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Although "cv." has not been permitted by the International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants since the 1995 edition, it is still widely used and recommended by other authorities.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Where several very similar cultivars exist they can be associated into a *Group* (formerly *Cultivar-group*).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] As Group names are used with cultivar names it is necessary to understand their way of presentation.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Group names are presented in normal type and the first letter of each word capitalised as for cultivars, but they are not placed in single quotes.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] When used in a name, the first letter of the word "Group" is itself capitalised.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Since the 1990s there has been an increasing use of legal protection for newly produced cultivars.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Plant breeders expect legal protection for the cultivars they produce.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] According to proponents of such protections, if other growers can immediately propagate and sell these cultivars as soon as they come on the market, the breeder's benefit is largely lost.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Legal protection for cultivars is obtained through the use of Plant breeders' rights and plant Patents but the specific legislation and procedures needed to take advantage of this protection vary from country to country.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The use of legal protection for cultivars can be controversial, particularly for food crops that are staples in developing countries, or for plants selected from the wild and propagated for sale without any additional breeding work; some people consider this practice unethical.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The formal scientific name of a cultivar, like *Solanum tuberosum* 'King Edward', is a way of uniquely designating a particular kind of plant.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] This scientific name is in the public domain and cannot be legally protected.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Plant retailers may wish to increase their share of the market, and one way of doing this is to replace the Latin scientific names on plant labels in retail outlets with appealing marketing names that are easy to use, pronounce, and remember.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Marketing names lie outside the scope of the *Cultivated Plant Code* which refers to them as "trade designations".
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] If a retailer or wholesaler has the sole legal rights to a marketing name then that may offer a sales advantage.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Plants protected by plant breeders' rights (PBR) may have a "true" cultivar name – the accepted scientific name in the public domain – and a "commercial synonym" – an additional marketing name that is legally protected.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] An example would be *Rosa* Fascination='Poulmax', in which *Rosa* is the genus, Fascination is the trade designation, and 'Poulmax' is scientific cultivar name.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Because a name that is attractive in one language may have less appeal in another country, a plant may be given different selling names from country to country.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Quoting the original cultivar name allows the correct identification of cultivars around the world.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The main body coordinating plant breeders' rights is the International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (*Union internationale pour la protection des obtentions végétales*, UPOV) and this organisation maintains a database of new cultivars protected by PBR in all countries.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] An *International Cultivar Registration Authority* (ICRA) is a voluntary, non-statutory organisation appointed by the *Commission for Nomenclature and Cultivar Registration* of the International Society of Horticultural Science.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] ICRAs are generally formed by societies and institutions specializing in particular plant genera such as *Dahlia* or *Rhododendron* and are currently located in Europe, North America, China, India, Singapore, Australia, New Zealand, South Africa and Puerto Rico.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Each ICRA produces an annual report and its reappointment is considered every four years.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The main task is to maintain a register of the names within the group of interest and where possible this is published and placed in the public domain.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] One major aim is to prevent the duplication of cultivar and Group epithets within a genus, as well as ensuring that names are in accord with the latest edition of the *Cultivated Plant Code*.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] In this way, over the last 50 years or so, ICRAs have contributed to the stability of cultivated plant nomenclature.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] In recent times many ICRAs have also recorded trade designations and trademarks used in labelling plant material, to avoid confusion with established names.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] New names and other relevant data are collected by and submitted to the ICRA and in most cases there is no cost.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] The ICRA then checks each new epithet to ensure that it has not been used before and that it conforms with the *Cultivated Plant Code*.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Each ICRA also ensures that new names are formally established (i.e. published in hard copy, with a description in a dated publication).
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] They record details about the plant, such as parentage, the names of those concerned with its development and introduction, and a basic description highlighting its distinctive characters.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] ICRAs are not responsible for assessing the distinctiveness of the plant in question.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/cultivar] Most ICRAs can be contacted electronically and many maintain web sites for an up-to-date listing.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] Flowers on short stalks (cymes) arise from compact rosettes of succulent fleshy, often brightly coloured leaves.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] Species are polycarpic, meaning that they may flower and set seed many times over the course of their lifetimes.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] Often, numerous offsets are produced, and are commonly known as "hen and chicks", which can also refer to other genera, such as *Sempervivum*, that are significantly different from *Echeveria*.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] Many species of *Echeveria* serve important environmental roles, such as those of host plants for butterflies.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] For example, the butterfly *Callophrys xami* uses several species of *Echeveria*, such as *Echeveria gibbiflora*, as suitable host plants.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] Even more, these plants are integral to the oviposition process of *C. xami* and some other butterfly species as well.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] P. de Candolle in 1828, and is named after the 18th century Mexican botanical artist Atanasio Echeverría y Godoy.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] As of June 2018, the genus consists of about 150 species, including genera such as *Oliveranthus* and *Urbinia* that have formerly been split off from *Echeveria*.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] Molecular phylogenetic studies have repeatedly shown the genus not to be monophyletic: species of *Echeveria* cluster with species of *Cremnophila*, *Graptopetalum*, *Pachyphytum*, and *Thompsonella* as well as species of *Sedum* sect.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] The former *Urbinia* species do appear to form a monophyletic group within this grouping.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] Although it is clear that *Echeveria* is not monophyletic, its limits are not clear, and further analyses are needed to determine whether and how the genus should be split, or if it should be included in an expanded concept of *Sedum*.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] Many *Echeveria* species are popular as ornamental garden plants.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] They are drought-resistant, although they do better with regular deep watering and fertilizing.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] Most will tolerate shade and some frost, although hybrids tend to be less tolerant.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] Most lose their lower leaves in winter; as a result, after a few years, the plants lose their compact appearance and need to be re-rooted or propagated.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] In addition, if not removed, the shed leaves may decay, harboring fungus that can then infect the plant.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/echeveria] They can be propagated easily by separating offsets, but also by leaf cuttings, and by seed if they are not hybrids.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/elizabeth-medal-of-honour] The **Elizabeth Medal of Honour** (**EMH**) is awarded to British non-horticulturalists and international horticultural and non-horticulturalists whose work has had a significant impact on the advancement of science, art or practice of horticulture.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/elizabeth-medal-of-honour] Therefore, the honour may not be awarded every year, but may be made to multiple recipients in other years.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/elizabeth-medal-of-honour] The Elizabeth Medal of Honour will join the Victoria Medal of Honour, which was established in 1897 with the consent of Her Majesty Queen Victoria, to enable the RHS Council to give the highest possible honour and recognition to Bristish horticulturalists by the Society.
[src:award-of-garden-merit/elizabeth-medal-of-honour] In recognition of the duration of Queen Victoria's reign only 63 medals may be held at any one time.
